    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about hiit workouts and kept seeing stuff about lactic acid. can u explain how it actually gets made in the muscles and how the body gets rid of it after a set? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Lactic acid is actually a byproduct of anaerobic glycolysis when your muscles need energy faster than oxygen can be supplied, leading to a rapid buildup that causes the familiar \"burn.\" The body clears it out primarily through the Cori cycle, where the liver converts the lactate back into glucose, which is then sent back to the muscles or used for energy. While HIIT workouts can temporarily elevate lactate levels, the body's natural mechanisms are quite efficient at neutralizing and removing it, often within a few hours after exercise.",
      "source": "target",
