    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "oh okay that makes sense. but it still feels like something is physically attacking my legs when i'm mid-sprint lol. like it's not just a chemical thing, it feels like there's this actual irritation or disruption happening in the muscle tissue specifically. is there a way to describe what that \"disruption\" actually looks like at a cellular level?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That sensation is largely caused by metabolites like hydrogen ions and inorganic phosphate interfering with calcium signaling, which prevents your muscles from relaxing and causes pain. At the cellular level, the disruption looks like a mess of \"metabolic acidosis\" where your mitochondria are overwhelmed, forcing your body to rely on inefficient anaerobic pathways that produce these irritants. While it feels like a physical attack, it is actually your cells screaming for oxygen before they can efficiently finish clearing out the waste products.",
